::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Overview of Perovskite solar cell advantages and the challenge of moisture-induced degradation."
::

# Introduction

Methylammonium lead halide perovskites (MAPhI3) have emerged as highly efficient 
light absorbers for third-generation photovoltaics @cite{kojima2009, snaith2013}. 
Despite reaching efficiencies over 25%, their commercial viability is 
limited by long-term stability issues, particularly in humid environments.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Fabrication of PSCs and description of the controlled humidity aging chambers."
::

# Experimental Methods

PSCs were fabricated using a standard spin-coating method in a nitrogen-filled 
glovebox. The cell architecture was FTO/TiO2/MAPbI3/Spiro-OMeTAD/Au. 
Aging tests were performed in custom-built environmental chambers with 
controlled humidity ($\pm 2\%$ RH).

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Degradation data and structural analysis via XRD."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results and Discussion

The time-resolved Power Conversion Efficiency (PCE) for cells aging at 
different RH levels is presented below.

::chart{#fig-pce-degradation}
::title Normalized PCE vs. aging time at various humidity levels
::interpretation
The chart clearly indicates a threshold effect at approximately 50% RH. 
Below this level, degradation is linear and slow. Above 60% RH, an 
exponential decay in efficiency is observed, coinciding with the 
formation of PbI2 as confirmed by X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns.
::
| Aging Time (h) | 20% RH PCE | 40% RH PCE | 60% RH PCE | 80% RH PCE |
|----------------|------------|------------|------------|------------|
| 0              | 1.00       | 1.00       | 1.00       | 1.00       |
| 50             | 0.99       | 0.98       | 0.85       | 0.32       |
| 100            | 0.98       | 0.96       | 0.72       | 0.05       |
| 250            | 0.95       | 0.92       | 0.40       | 0.00       |
| 500            | 0.92       | 0.88       | 0.15       | 0.00       |
::endchart

::equation{#eq-degradation-rate}
$$
\eta(t) = \eta_0 \exp(-k_{hum} \cdot t)
$$
::label Humidity-dependent efficiency decay model
::endequation

where $k_{hum}$ is the humidity-dependent degradation constant.

::endsection


::section{#conclusion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Summary of findings and strategies for improving PSC stability."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Conclusion

We have quantified the critical humidity thresholds for MAPbI3 solar cells. 
Encapsulation strategies or the use of 2D/3D hybrid perovskites are 
necessary for deployment in tropical or high-humidity regions.

::endsection
